    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''If a Swing State Cares, It's an Issue,'' by Michael Lind (Op-Ed, Oct. 2): Reform of the Electoral College may be a good idea, but a more meaningful change would be the addition of ''none of the above'' to a line on the ballot with the provision that if ''none of the above'' received more votes than any candidate, the parties would be required to nominate new candidates and another election held in four to six weeks.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''If a Swing State Cares, It's an Issue,'' by Michael Lind (Op-Ed, Oct. 2): Reform of the Electoral College may be a good idea, but a more meaningful change would be the addition of ''none of the above'' to a line on the ballot with the provision that if ''none of the above'' received more votes than any candidate, the parties would be required to nominate new candidates and another election held in four to six weeks.</p>
        <p>To avoid this rejection and embarrassment, such a change might inspire the parties to nominate people of quality, ending what many believe is too often the choice between bad and worse or not voting at all.</p>
        <p>RICH GREENER  Roswell, Ga., Oct. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
